<Post {...meta}>

<p>The first version was called TimeBot. It did what it said. It was accurate and it was functional and it had no personality.</p>

<p>The name mattered more than we expected. When you call something a bot, people interact with it like a bot — formally, carefully, on its terms. When you give something a name, people talk to it like they'd talk to a colleague. They're less precise. They're more natural. And natural language is exactly what we needed.</p>

<p>VERA — Versatile Enterprise Resource Assistant, though nobody needs to know that — signals something different. It's a colleague, not a command line. You don't fill in VERA's form. You tell VERA what you did.</p>

<p>The change was small. The shift in how people used it was not.</p>

</Post>
